SIMPLE: eustachian
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eustachian
<hw>Eu*sta"chi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>Eustachi</ets>, a learned Italian physician who died in Rome,
1574.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Discovered by
Eustachius.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Pertaining to the Eustachian tube;
<as>as, <ex>Eustachian</ex> catheter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Eustachian catheter</b></col>, <cd>a tubular instrument
to be introduced into the Eustachian tube so as to allow of inflation of
the middle ear through the nose or mouth.</cd> -- <col><b>Eustrachian
tube</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a passage from the tympanum of
the ear to the pharynx. See <er>Ear</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Eustachian
valve</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a crescent-shaped fold of the
lining membrane of the heart at the entrance of the vena cava inferior.
It directs the blood towards the left auricle in the fetus, but is
rudimentary and functionless in the adult.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eustyle</ent>⟦br⟧
